    <segment id="1" parent="11" relname="circumstance">
As I was scanning the ACM SIGCHI database</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="19" relname="span"> I found this article about the now famous or 
infamous Florida elections of 2000 and 2002.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="18" relname="span"> Savage (2003), places the fault squarely on 
HCI professionals.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="13" relname="concession"> He mentions that few reporters know what HCI is,</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="15" relname="span"> but he remains 
shocked that so many of the articles concerning the problem did not focus on the fact 
that these systems should be designed for regular people.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="13" relname="elaboration"> In fact he points out that 
most people still expect new technology to be complicated to use.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="5" relname="antithesis"> The article implies 
that the operators of the ballot boxes needed 12 hours of training in its use.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="17" relname="span"> That is a bit 
off the 10-Minute mark set in our text.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="20" relname="span">

Frankly, I did not think about this problem in this way until I read this article.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration"> I found 
myself blaming those individuals who could not properly learn to vote.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="21" relname="span"> I find it hard to 
believe we could find a system that would have more potential for end-user collaborative 
design and implementation than the voting system.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="14" relname="circumstance"> Given that NOVA is based in Florida,</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="23" relname="span"> 
does anyone in the class have a contact with the company building the replacement 
system?</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="14" relname="evaluation"> What an interesting opportunity to see if the HCI concepts are being used.</segment>
